          "body": "Job 27 opens with the most solemn possible speech act in the ancient world: a sworn oath on the life of God. 'As God lives' (*chai-El*, 27:2) — the standard Hebrew oath form, binding the speaker to total truthfulness on pain of divine judgment. The electric irony is that Job invokes as witness the very God he is about to charge with injustice ('who has taken away my right'). This is not contradiction; it is the most paradoxical form of faith — the faith that cries out to God against God, that refuses to abandon the relationship even while disputing the verdict. Calvin saw in Job the model of a man who never mistakes candor before God for impiety toward God.\n\nThe content of the oath is Job's moral integrity: lips that will not speak unjustly, a tongue that will not mutter deceit (27:4), integrity (*tummah*) that will not be surrendered until death (27:5), righteousness (*tsedaqah*) held fast like something gripped against those who would tear it away (27:6). These are not idle claims. *Tummah* is the precise word God Himself used of Job in 1:8 — 'blameless and upright.' Job is not asserting a righteousness he has invented; he is refusing to deny the character God's own words have already ascribed to him.\n\nThe friends have spent twenty-six chapters demanding that Job confess — that he admit secret sin, acknowledge his suffering as deserved punishment, and so 'declare them right' (27:5). Job's answer here is the clearest possible: *Far be it from me.* This is not stubbornness; it is truth-telling under maximum social and theological pressure. To confess what you have not done, in order to satisfy the demands of your community, is the lie. Job chooses truth over peace and holds it until death."
